      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>As with any team, the <strong>attitudes and behaviour of the team</strong> will be a significant factor in determining whether a trainee succeeds or not. A <strong>positive</strong> and <strong>encouraging</strong> approach to a trainee will go a long way to allowing them to transition from 'newbie' to fulling included member of the team.</p>

        <h2>Situational awareness</h2>

        <p>As an OJTI, one of the competencies that is important in managing the trainee's integration into the team is '<strong>situational awareness</strong>'. Normally we talk about situational awareness in the context of awareness of traffic, but in training, an OJTI also needs to develop situational awareness of the <strong>impact the trainee has on any of the other team members</strong> and how that might be affecting their ability to integrate into the team.</p>

      </div>

      <div class="ians-column-wide-2">

        {% image "images/situational_awareness.jpg", "Situational awareness"%}
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>This awareness may be related to an awareness of the <strong>attitude of the trainee</strong> (positive or negative), that affects other controllers (we did an example of this in the previous section). It may how the trainee's actions affect other team members. Or, it may be how other team members are behaving towards the trainee and how that impacts their performance.</p>

        <h2>Harmonising OJTI instructing</h2>

        <p>One of the major challenges faced by any ATCO training team is the difficulty in achieving <strong>consistent instruction and assessment across all the OJTIs</strong>. The biggest concern for many trainees is that they are given conflicting advice and instruction by different OJTIs. This is understandable and to an extent, a competency-based approach puts in place tools and processes that reduce these differences. However, competency-based training and assessment methods cannot completely eliminate all differences and neither is it intended to do so.</p>

