      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>Nonetheless, there can be significant benefits in carrying out <strong>team activities</strong> that are focussed on harmonising the interpretation and assessment of various air traffic events and trainees' behaviours. For example, a group of <strong>OJTIs can all observe a performance together</strong> and then evaluate it using their competency model for that environment. This will allow significant differences in interpretation and assessment of a performance to become visible and give everyone an opportunity to discuss and harmonise their approach.</p>

        <p>Another team activity that has resulted in enhanced OJTI performance, is to let <strong>one OJTI provide instruction to another OJTI</strong> and then to provide feedback to each other with the aim of identifying strengths and areas that could improve.</p>

        <p>Whichever way an OJTI receives feedback on their instructional competency, either from a colleague, another OJTI, a student or an assessor; <strong>what they do with this feedback</strong> shows their <strong>attitude</strong> towards OJT. Do they take it on-board, evaluate it, adapt and learn or do they dismiss it or see it as a threat and challenge it?</p>
